HEADWORD: Sophisticate
<hw>So*phis"ti*cate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Sophisticated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sophisticating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL.
<ets>sophisticatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>sophisticare</ets> to
sophisticate.]</ety> <def>To render worthless by admixture; to
adulterate; to damage; to pervert; <as>as, to <ex>sophisticate</ex>
wine</as>.</def> <rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>sophisticate</qex> the understanding.</q>
<rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet Butler professes to stick to plain facts, not to
<qex>sophisticate</qex>, not to refine.</q> <rj><qau>M.
Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They purchase but <qex>sophisticated</qex> ware.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To adulterate; debase; corrupt;
vitiate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

